1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,500
Good morning, everyone, and thank you for your time.

2
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:12,000
Over the next ten minutes, I'll introduce our product — AgenticMMM — and give you a live,

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:18,600
end-to-end demonstration of how it delivers a real Marketing Mix Modeling project.

4
00:00:20,600 --> 00:00:27,100
Before I begin, let me take one minute to frame the problem we set out to solve.

5
00:00:29,100 --> 00:00:34,900
Marketing Mix Modeling — MMM for short — is a well-established discipline in marketing science.

6
00:00:36,900 --> 00:00:42,700
It answers the question every marketing leader cares about most: for every dollar I spend,

7
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:47,400
how much business does it actually generate?

8
00:00:49,400 --> 00:00:54,400
TV, e-commerce, offline, promotions — what is each channel's true contribution to sales?

9
00:00:56,400 --> 00:00:58,700
What is the return on investment?

10
00:01:00,700 --> 00:01:04,900
If I increase or cut a budget, how will sales respond?

11
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:11,900
And how should I reallocate next quarter's budget across channels to maximize return?

12
00:01:13,900 --> 00:01:19,300
MMM answers these questions quantitatively, through statistical modeling on historical sales and media data.

13
00:01:21,300 --> 00:01:28,600
Its value is beyond dispute — but the way it has traditionally been delivered carries a fundamental pain point.

14
00:01:30,600 --> 00:01:34,800
And that is exactly what I want to talk about today.

15
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:44,500
A traditional MMM project typically takes six to twelve weeks and relies on a dedicated team of consultants, data engineers,

16
00:01:46,500 --> 00:01:48,100
and modeling scientists.

17
00:01:50,100 --> 00:01:55,900
But the core burden of this delivery model is not the time it takes —

18
00:01:57,900 --> 00:02:02,100
it is that it places an extraordinary cognitive load on people.

19
00:02:04,100 --> 00:02:10,600
In a traditional, process-driven delivery, every step depends heavily on expert judgment: how to structure the factors,

20
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:19,100
which data is usable, how to set the model priors, whether the results align with business logic.

21
00:02:21,100 --> 00:02:28,400
And on top of making these judgments, the experts must also carry out an enormous amount of mechanical, repetitive,

22
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:35,000
low-value execution — cleaning data, aligning formats, tuning parameters over and over.

23
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:40,800
The high-order cognition of experts gets buried under low-order labor.

24
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:47,800
The design philosophy of AgenticMMM is built entirely around relieving that cognitive load.

25
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:52,100
We distill it into three principles.

26
00:02:54,100 --> 00:02:59,900
Principle one: draw a clear line between three roles — AI, Human, and Machine —

27
00:03:01,900 --> 00:03:06,900
and assign every piece of work to whichever is best suited to it.

28
00:03:08,900 --> 00:03:12,700
We classify every task in the project into three kinds:

29
00:03:14,700 --> 00:03:20,100
- Machine handles deterministic computation — data extraction and transformation, regression fitting, quality scoring.

30
00:03:22,100 --> 00:03:28,300
This work has exactly one correct answer, so we hand it to code: fast and error-free.

31
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:35,300
- AI handles grounded generation — business interpretation, key business questions, decision recommendations.

32
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:44,600
This work requires understanding and expression, but it must be built strictly on real data and real model results.

33
00:03:46,600 --> 00:03:53,100
- Human handles judgment and decisions — the critical junctures that require business experience, trade-offs, and accountability.

34
00:03:55,100 --> 00:04:03,600
This division of labor frees the expert entirely from mechanical labor and concentrates their cognitive resources where a human is truly needed.

35
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:11,400
Principle two: Human-in-the-Loop, or HITL — ensuring people step in only when it is necessary.

36
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:15,000
This is critical.

37
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:23,200
We do not chase full automation, nor do we exhaust people by making them confirm everything.

38
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:29,400
The system places decision nodes at every critical quality gate —

39
00:04:31,400 --> 00:04:36,400
the workflow deliberately blocks there and waits for human confirmation, while everywhere else,

40
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:41,100
AI and Machine advance autonomously, without interruption.

41
00:04:43,100 --> 00:04:46,900
Here is an example: data validation uses a three-state score.

42
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:55,800
A pass is cleared automatically; an unusable metric is discarded automatically with an alert; and only the borderline,

43
00:04:57,800 --> 00:05:00,900
questionable metrics bring a person into the decision.

44
00:05:02,900 --> 00:05:09,400
A person's attention is therefore directed precisely to where judgment is most needed, rather than consumed indiscriminately.

45
00:05:11,400 --> 00:05:15,200
Principle three works on two levels — Artifacts-Driven and Human-Intuitive.

46
00:05:17,200 --> 00:05:23,000
Being Artifacts-Driven means the entire workflow is organized around concrete deliverables, rather than an opaque,

47
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:26,600
black-box process.

48
00:05:28,600 --> 00:05:30,500
This yields four practical benefits.

49
00:05:32,500 --> 00:05:37,900
First, visible progress — the status of every deliverable is clear at a glance.

50
00:05:39,900 --> 00:05:45,700
Second, controllable quality — every deliverable is a natural unit for human review and sign-off.

51
00:05:47,700 --> 00:05:51,900
Third, full traceability — every deliverable carries version history and lineage,

52
00:05:53,900 --> 00:06:01,600
so the final report can be traced all the way back to the model, data, and interviews it rests on.

53
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:07,400
Fourth, reliable propagation — the moment a deliverable is rejected,

54
00:06:09,400 --> 00:06:15,600
every affected downstream output is automatically reset and rebuilt, so no inconsistency is ever left behind.

55
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:22,200
Being Human-Intuitive means the system presents work the way a person thinks,

56
00:06:24,200 --> 00:06:28,400
rather than forcing the person to adapt to the machine's logic.

57
00:06:30,400 --> 00:06:35,800
A project unfolds naturally along the hierarchy of Stage → Deliverable → build process;

58
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:45,500
business factors are presented as an intuitive factor tree; items requiring a decision are gathered into a single, clear inbox.

59
00:06:47,500 --> 00:06:55,200
The user needs to learn no complex system concepts — everything is presented in the business language they already know.

60
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:02,600
Built on this philosophy, the core of the product is carried by three interfaces.

61
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:06,500
Let me walk through each.

62
00:07:08,500 --> 00:07:10,100
First, Workflow.

63
00:07:12,100 --> 00:07:18,300
This is the methodology blueprint the product crystallizes, visualized as a directed acyclic graph, a DAG.

64
00:07:20,300 --> 00:07:26,500
The horizontal axis is the five delivery stages; the vertical swim lanes are the five agents.

65
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:36,200
Every task node is labeled with its collaboration mode — whether it is executed autonomously by Machine, generated by AI,

66
00:07:38,200 --> 00:07:39,800
or requires human intervention.

67
00:07:41,800 --> 00:07:46,400
Click any node to see its inputs, outputs, dependencies, and reasoning log.

68
00:07:48,400 --> 00:07:53,000
This single diagram is the complete picture of how the project runs.

69
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:56,600
Second, Project.

70
00:07:58,600 --> 00:08:05,100
This is the primary workspace for execution and delivery, and the direct embodiment of the Artifacts-Driven principle.

71
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:15,900
The interface is organized along the hierarchy of Stage spine → Deliverable list → build process: the stage progress sits at the top,

72
00:08:17,900 --> 00:08:26,400
the full set of deliverables for that stage on the left, and the main area shows exactly how each deliverable is built.

73
00:08:28,400 --> 00:08:33,000
The real materials a project needs are uploaded through the Project Folder;

74
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:38,100
items requiring human confirmation are handled right here.

75
00:08:40,100 --> 00:08:44,300
All of the user's day-to-day work happens in this one interface.

76
00:08:46,300 --> 00:08:47,900
Third, Knowledge.

77
00:08:49,900 --> 00:08:53,400
This is the platform's hub for accumulation and reuse.

78
00:08:55,400 --> 00:09:01,900
MMM industry knowledge — factor templates, interview frameworks, validation rules — is accumulated here, organized by industry,

79
00:09:03,900 --> 00:09:05,500
editable, maintainable, and versioned.

80
00:09:07,500 --> 00:09:11,700
Every new project inherits the relevant industry's knowledge base from here;

81
00:09:13,700 --> 00:09:20,600
and every confirmation and correction a person makes during a project flows back and enriches this knowledge base.

82
00:09:22,600 --> 00:09:26,400
The platform therefore grows smarter with every project it runs.

83
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:31,900
Enough talk — let the results speak for themselves.

84
00:09:33,900 --> 00:09:43,100
What I have open here is a project that has already run to completion — a real modeling dataset of some twenty thousand rows.

85
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:50,500
Traditionally, this is six to twelve weeks of output from a full expert team.

86
00:09:52,500 --> 00:09:57,900
Over the next few minutes, I'll walk you through its results from the top,

87
00:09:59,900 --> 00:10:08,700
and I'd ask you to watch just one thing: behind these results, how did the three roles — AI, Human, and Machine —

88
00:10:10,700 --> 00:10:13,800
divide the work and collaborate to produce them.

89
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:17,400
Stage one, Business Understanding.

90
00:10:19,400 --> 00:10:27,900
This used to be the most cognitively demanding part of the entire project — a consultant poring over the Statement of Work,

91
00:10:29,900 --> 00:10:35,300
industry reports, and a dozen interview transcripts, then hand-drawing a factor tree from experience.

92
00:10:37,300 --> 00:10:45,400
The project scope you see here was framed automatically by the Business Agent after it read the client's SOW: product lines,

93
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:50,500
channels, regions, and time granularity, all of it.

94
00:10:52,500 --> 00:10:57,900
And this entire factor tree was generated by it drawing on industry knowledge —

95
00:10:59,900 --> 00:11:06,800
from the top-level business drivers all the way down to modelable metrics, each factor matched with its indicators;

96
00:11:08,800 --> 00:11:15,700
the common parts recalled directly, the specific parts added by it on its own, with their sources labeled.

97
00:11:17,700 --> 00:11:20,800
And the crux is in these flagged nodes.

98
00:11:22,800 --> 00:11:27,400
AI ran through the entire process, yet it never decided for anyone.

99
00:11:29,400 --> 00:11:36,700
Every factor the AI added was, at the time, placed in front of a person to confirm or reject;

100
00:11:38,700 --> 00:11:45,600
and every one of those judgments flowed back into the knowledge base, making the platform smarter with use.

101
00:11:47,600 --> 00:11:53,400
This is what AI-Native collaboration looks like: AI and Machine carry all the heavy lifting,

102
00:11:55,400 --> 00:12:00,000
and the human appears only where a real decision must be made.

103
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:05,100
The interview step shows this even more fully.

104
00:12:07,100 --> 00:12:15,600
This interview outline was generated by the agent after it had first read all existing materials and drafted its own first-pass answers,

105
00:12:17,600 --> 00:12:23,400
leaving only the questions that truly needed validating in person; once the notes came back,

106
00:12:25,400 --> 00:12:31,900
it compared them automatically and highlighted, right on the factor tree, what should change and why —

107
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:36,200
the person only had to confirm.

108
00:12:38,200 --> 00:12:41,700
Following on, this is the data-request document it generated,

109
00:12:43,700 --> 00:12:50,200
and the single Business Understanding summary into which it folded the scope, factor tree, and interview insights.

110
00:12:52,200 --> 00:12:58,000
A stage that once took weeks — its results, all here in front of you.

111
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:02,300
Stage two, Data Intake & Quality.

112
00:13:04,300 --> 00:13:12,800
Once the data was back, this used to be a data engineer's most grueling weeks — cleaning, aligning, checking column by column.

113
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:21,300
This deterministic work, the kind with exactly one right answer, was taken over entirely by the Machine.

114
00:13:23,300 --> 00:13:29,800
Look at this data-quality scorecard: the system scores every metric across a few dimensions — consistency, accuracy,

115
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:33,400
comprehensiveness, granularity.

116
00:13:35,400 --> 00:13:44,200
A full score is cleared automatically, a failing one is discarded with an alert — the vast majority, it handles on its own.

117
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:54,700
And this flagged metric is the one that landed on the borderline and was brought specifically to a person to decide —

118
00:13:56,700 --> 00:14:01,300
the human's attention landed precisely on the one place that needed judgment.

119
00:14:03,300 --> 00:14:07,100
Once validation passes, the multi-source data is automatically cleaned, mapped,

120
00:14:09,100 --> 00:14:15,300
and integrated into this unified wide-table master dataset on the right, together with a data dictionary.

121
00:14:17,300 --> 00:14:23,500
Notice one elegant thing: the columns of this wide table are the factor tree itself —

122
00:14:25,500 --> 00:14:30,100
the business structure and the data structure are one and the same.

123
00:14:32,100 --> 00:14:35,900
From raw data to final dataset, every step is traceable.

124
00:14:37,900 --> 00:14:39,800
Stage three, Validation & Hypotheses.

125
00:14:41,800 --> 00:14:48,000
Clean isn't enough — the data has to withstand two interrogations at once: business, and statistical.

126
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:55,800
First, business validation: the Data Agent drills down through the factor tree layer by layer,

127
00:14:57,800 --> 00:15:00,500
checking whether each metric makes commercial sense,

128
00:15:02,500 --> 00:15:10,200
then auto-generates charts and trend interpretations for the client to sign off on — another gate guarded by a human.

129
00:15:12,200 --> 00:15:18,400
Once cleared comes statistical validation: it screens each metric with coefficient of variation, correlation, and collinearity,

130
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:26,600
then runs a quick regression pre-fit to produce rough contribution and ROI ranges for each factor,

131
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:30,500
finally locking the model input.

132
00:15:32,500 --> 00:15:39,800
And more importantly, this stage also distilled the modeling priors — the likely elasticity range of a given channel,

133
00:15:41,800 --> 00:15:46,400
that a competitor's effect should be negative, that brand search leads sales.

134
00:15:48,400 --> 00:15:54,900
Each of these hypotheses was confirmed by the client, becoming a constraint for the next stage's modeling.

135
00:15:56,900 --> 00:16:00,700
Business intuition and statistical rigor, brought together in one system.

136
00:16:02,700 --> 00:16:04,300
Stage four, Modeling.

137
00:16:06,300 --> 00:16:10,900
First, model choice: when you need to iterate ROI quickly, use OLS;

138
00:16:12,900 --> 00:16:21,000
when you need high precision and want to feed business priors in to guide the result, use a Bayesian probabilistic model.

139
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:28,000
Those business hypotheses from the last stage were translated here into mathematical constraints.

140
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:38,800
Here I'll draw a hard line: every number you see in the report — adstock, saturation curves, each channel's contribution and ROI —

141
00:16:40,800 --> 00:16:47,300
comes from a real regression engine, computed one by one, not conjured up by a language model.

142
00:16:49,300 --> 00:16:55,800
AI-Native never means letting AI make things up; what should be computed is left, faithfully, to computation.

143
00:16:57,800 --> 00:17:04,700
After tuning comes technical validation — and not on a single metric: goodness of fit, prediction accuracy, residuals,

144
00:17:06,700 --> 00:17:12,100
contribution decomposition, all cross-validated across dimensions, where any single red flag stops the model.

145
00:17:14,100 --> 00:17:17,900
Only when all of that passes does model selection come.

146
00:17:19,900 --> 00:17:25,300
These here are the Pareto-optimal candidates the system produced, laid out side by side.

147
00:17:27,300 --> 00:17:34,600
The system never picks for anyone automatically — the one finally chosen was this one, owned by a person.

148
00:17:36,600 --> 00:17:40,800
Because choosing a model is, at its core, a business trade-off.

149
00:17:42,800 --> 00:17:44,400
Stage five, Reporting.

150
00:17:46,400 --> 00:17:51,400
The Report Agent turned cold coefficients into an entire language the business understands.

151
00:17:53,400 --> 00:18:01,500
Look at this report: the decomposition chart shows you how sales break down into Base plus the contribution of each channel;

152
00:18:03,500 --> 00:18:09,700
the Due-to chart attributes 'why did sales rise or fall this period' to each individual channel;

153
00:18:11,700 --> 00:18:16,700
the ROI chart sets every channel's return next to an industry benchmark line,

154
00:18:18,700 --> 00:18:25,600
with a reminder that upper-funnel channels have naturally lower ROI yet real value, and can't be extrapolated linearly.

155
00:18:27,600 --> 00:18:33,800
Every chart is a templated chart plus AI adding business-contextual narration — both standard and business-savvy.

156
00:18:35,800 --> 00:18:42,700
And you can question it directly, say, 'Why does this channel have the highest ROI?' — it answers,

157
00:18:44,700 --> 00:18:47,000
grounded in the real model results.

158
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:55,900
But here is the real highlight: the model is not the finish line — it's the starting line.

159
00:18:57,900 --> 00:19:06,000
This simulator, delivered to the client, can be re-run at any time — set the total budget and your business constraints,

160
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:12,200
and it runs a marginal optimization on the real response curves,

161
00:19:14,200 --> 00:19:18,800
telling you directly how to split the money for the greatest return.

162
00:19:20,800 --> 00:19:26,200
Traditionally, a modeling team would compute this one question for days; here, it's seconds,

163
00:19:28,200 --> 00:19:32,400
and you can play out as many scenarios as you like.

164
00:19:34,400 --> 00:19:41,300
A real MMM project, carried all the way from a single SOW to an executable budget recommendation —

165
00:19:43,300 --> 00:19:45,600
that is what it ultimately delivers.

166
00:19:47,600 --> 00:19:53,400
In a little over ten minutes, we have walked through a complete, real MMM project.

167
00:19:55,400 --> 00:19:57,700
Let me close on three points.

168
00:19:59,700 --> 00:20:02,000
First, this is AI-Native, not AI-attached.

169
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:11,300
We did not bolt a chat box onto legacy software; we rebuilt from the skeleton of the process outward.

170
00:20:13,300 --> 00:20:19,800
The methodology is crystallized into a visible workflow, AI, Human, and Machine each play their proper role,

171
00:20:21,800 --> 00:20:26,400
and AI reaches into every step rather than floating on the surface.

172
00:20:28,400 --> 00:20:34,200
Second, it relieves the cognitive burden on people — it does not replace their judgment.

173
00:20:36,200 --> 00:20:42,700
Machine takes on mechanical computation, AI takes on grounded generation, and the human — through Human-in-the-Loop —

174
00:20:44,700 --> 00:20:52,400
is called precisely to every juncture that genuinely requires judgment: not one interruption too many, not one checkpoint too few.

175
00:20:54,400 --> 00:20:59,400
Everything is artifacts-driven, visible, and traceable, presented in a way people already understand.

176
00:21:01,400 --> 00:21:06,000
Third, it delivers not just a report, but a lasting decision capability.

177
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:15,700
Once the model is complete, you can return to the simulator at any time to play out any budget scenario;

178
00:21:17,700 --> 00:21:22,300
and the platform keeps evolving as each project deposits knowledge into it.

179
00:21:24,300 --> 00:21:33,100
For a brand, this means three things: a faster delivery cycle, a lower project cost, and — because the entire process is visible,

180
00:21:35,100 --> 00:21:38,600
controllable, and traceable — results you can trust more.

181
00:21:40,600 --> 00:21:42,200
Thank you.

182
00:21:44,200 --> 00:21:50,000
I'd be glad to run through any specific scenario you care about, live, right now.
